did.abstract: The collection includes information about and examples of the work of male amateur and commercial photographers, studio assistants, photographic processors, colorists, photojournalists, film makers, and film theaters collected by Peter Palmquist from 1971 until his death in 2003. The collection documents the practice and occupation of photography in Humboldt County, California, from around the incorporation of the county in 1853. This collection consists of biographical files collected by Palmquist for over nine hundred men and businesses involved in photography and photographic materials that represent the work of nearly three hundred individuals and firms. Individual photographers with significant quantities of material in the collection include Ray Jerome Baker, Augustus William Ericson, Amasa Plummer Flaglor, Alexius Alexander Holmes, N. B. Strong, and Joshua P. Vansant. Firms with substantial groups of material in the collection include the Arcata Union newspaper, Art-Ray Company, Freeman Art Co., and Seely Studio.

Books and periodicals formerly in the personal library of Peter Palmquist are accessible via the library catalog by conducting an advanced search of special collections with the search string: "Palmquist, Peter E., Ownership."

bioghist.head: Peter E. Palmquist (1936-2003)
bioghist.p: A photographer, collector, and historian of photography, Peter Eric Palmquist was born in Oakland, California on September 23, 1936. In 1944, he moved with his family to Ferndale, California, and he spent most of his life in Humboldt County. During adolescence, Palmquist trained himself in photography. He served in the United States Army as a photographer from 1955 to 1959, mainly with the Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe in Paris, France. Palmquist worked briefly as a photographer for the state government of California from 1959-1961. From 1961 until his retirement in 1989, Palmquist worked as a staff photographer for Humboldt State University, Arcata, California, where he also graduated with a Bachelor of Arts degree in Art in 1965.

From 1971 until his death, Palmquist collected textual materials and hundreds of thousands of photographic items documenting the practice and occupation of photography from its beginning through the turn of the twenty-first century. He had particular interests in early California photographers, photographers of the American West, and women photographers.

A self-trained researcher and historian of photography, Palmquist organized more than a hundred exhibitions and wrote more than three hundred articles and a hundred monographs. He was a founding editor of The Daguerreian Annual ; president of the National Stereoscopic Association.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection includes information about and examples of the work of male amateur and commercial photographers, studio assistants, photographic processors, colorists, photojournalists, film makers, and film theaters collected by Peter Palmquist from 1971 until his death in 2003. The collection documents the practice and occupation of photography in Humboldt County, California, from the incorporation of the county in 1853. This collection consists of biographical files collected by Palmquist for over nine hundred men and businesses involved in photography and photographic materials that represent the work of nearly three hundred individuals and firms. A database http://beinecke.library.yale.edu/palmquist_humboldt/ provides individual name access to men with biographical files, as well as any available information regarding their aliases, working locations, life dates, and work dates. Individual photographers with significant quantities of material in the collection include Ray Jerome Baker, Augustus William Ericson, Amasa Plummer Flaglor, Alexius Alexander Holmes, N. B. Strong, and Joshua P. Vansant. Firms with substantial groups of material in the collection include the Arcata Union newspaper, Art-Ray Company, Freeman Art Co., and Seely Studio.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into two series: I. Biographical Files, 1971-2003. II. Photographic Materials, circa 1850-2003.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is intellectually arranged alphabetically by personal or corporate name. The physical arrangement compiles smaller quantities by individuals and firms in the same box. while others are housed in one or more boxes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of biographical files and volumes that document over nine hundred men and firms involved with photography in Humboldt County, California, from 1853 to 2003. Palmquist and his assistants compiled much of the material from secondary sources between 1971 and 2003.

This portion of the finding aid provides access to ranges of boxes holding hundreds of individual biographical files. Researchers may also consult a database http://beinecke.library.yale.edu/palmquist_humboldt/ that provides individual name access to men and firms represented in this series, as well as any available information regarding their aliases, working locations, life dates, and work dates.

The contents of individual biographical files range from a single sheet providing the name of a man or firm to more comprehensive information, such as his life and work dates and his working locations, as well as professional or personal acquaintances.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Archival Materials note
relatedmaterial.p: Biographical information related to women photographers active in Humboldt County, California, are included in Peter Palmquist Collection of Women in Photography (WA MSS S-2600).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Series II is organized into five subseries: Photographic Materials; Photograph Albums, Oversize Photographic Materials; Glass Negatives and Transparencies; and Film Negatives.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of photographic materials collected by Palmquist that were created by or document individual male photographers or photographic firms.

This series consists of vintage photographic prints, as well as a significant quantity of copy photographs created by Palmquist of vintage photographic prints. The series documents the breadth of work by male photographers in Humboldt County from the middle of the nineteenth century to the late twentieth century. Works by a photographer may appear in multiple subseries.

For most of the listed photographers, the collection has only a few photographs. However, there are significant quantities of photographs by Ray Jerome Baker, Augustus William Ericson, Amasa Plummer Flaglor, Alexius Alexander Holmes, N. B. Strong, and Joshua P. Vansant. Firms with significant quantity of material in the collection include the Arcata Union newspaper, Art-Ray Company, Freeman Art Co., and Seely Studio.
Specific dates of materials or image creation dates were not captured during processing.
Nearly all of the individuals and firms with photographic materials in this series have biographical files in Series I.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Archival Materials note
relatedmaterial.p: Photographic materials related to women photographers active in Humboldt County, California, are included in Peter Palmquist Collection of Women in Photography (WA MSS S-2600).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This subseries is arranged alphabetically by the surname of the photographer or the corporate name of the studio followed by photographs by unidentified photographers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries consists of vintage photographic prints, copy photographs, 35 millimeter color slides, photographic negatives, associated publications, and ephemera. Photographic materials with dimensions larger than 22 x 29 cm (8.7 x 11.4 in.) are located in the Oversize Photographic Materials subseries.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Photographs and negatives from the Arcata Union newspaper are arranged into two groupings acccording to format, and then roughly chronologically.

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Arcata Union was a weekly newspaper that published from 1886 to 1995 in and for the city of Arcata, California

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries chiefly consists of nitrate film negatives created by or documenting individual photographers. Nitrate film negatives are cellulose treated with sulfuric acid and potassium nitrate to create cellulose mononitrate, also known as commercially as Celluloid, a highly flammable plastic used in the first half of the twentieth century for photographic film.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Restricted Fragile Material in boxes 148-160 may be consulted only with permission of the appropriate curator. These boxes contain nitrate base film that is relatively unstable and a fire hazard.
